The Apache POI library does not provide a direct way to identify blank cells in an Excel file. However, you can use a workaround to achieve this by checking the value of the cell and comparing it with an empty string.

Here's an updated code snippet that checks if the cell value is empty and skips it if it is:
```java
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.Iterator;
import org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.XSSFCell;
import org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.XSSFRow;
import org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.XSSFSheet;
import org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.XSSFWorkbook;

public class ExcelBlankCellValue {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        String fileName = "example.xlsx"; // Replace with your Excel file name

        FileInputStream inputStr = new FileInputStream(fileName);
        XSSFWorkbook xssfWork = new XSSFWorkbook(inputStr);
        XSSFSheet sheet1 = xssfWork.getSheetAt(0);

        Iterator<XSSFRow> rowItr = sheet1.rowIterator();
        while (rowItr.hasNext()) {
            XSSFRow row = (XSSFRow) rowItr.next();
            Iterator<XSSFCell> cellItr = row.cellIterator();
            while (cellItr.hasNext()) {
                XSSFCell cell = (XSSFCell) cellItr.next();
                if (cell.getStringCellValue().isEmpty()) {
                    System.out.println("CELL:-->" + cell.getStringCellValue());
                } else {
                    System.out.println("CELL:-->" + cell.getStringCellValue() + " (not empty)");
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```
This code checks if the cell value is empty using the `isEmpty()` method of the `String` class. If the value is empty, it prints the cell value, otherwise, it prints a message indicating that the cell value is not empty.
